title.narrative: 3.1. FULL DEVELOPMENT IN EARLY CHILDHOOD

description.narrative: By 2021, the capacity of the State and society for the coordinated design and management of equitable and relevant policies for full development in early childhood (0â€“5 years) in the priority territories will have been built., which contributes to Access To Justice, Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Birth Registration, Child Health, Early Childhood Development, Early Childhood Development (Covid), Early Learning, Health Systems Strengthening, Infant And Young Child Feeding, Learning Outcomes, Maternal And Newborn Health, Nutrition And Emergencies, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Social Protection, Social Protection And Child Poverty, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2021, children exposed to concerns related to gender, ethnicity, area of residence, living conditions or differences in skills will live in safe environments and have full access to relevant and quality registration, health, nutrition, care, education, water, sanitation and hygiene services that promote their full development.

title.narrative: By 2021, the capacity of the State and society for the coordinated design and management of equitable and relevant policies for full development in early childhood (0–5 years) in the priority territories will have been built.

description.narrative: ECD policies: “Primero la Infancia” (Childhood First) policy and the design of the RBBP ECD are being implemented with UNICEF technical guidance. This guidance consisted of evidence analysis, methodologies for the implementation of a comprehensive approach to early childhood development, training of ECD service providers, monitoring, and intersectoral coordination. UNICEF led initiatives at local/regional are contributing to improve quality of services, increase budget allocation, improve intersectoral coordination, and serve as a model to design and implement public policies. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:31/12/2019
